<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06200229 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06200229 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Amiram Nir  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  IRAN; KIDNAPPING; WRITING; ROBBERY; ISRAEL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The widow of Amiram Nir, the Israeli counter-terrorism expert who played a keyrole in the Iran-Contra scandal, has reported that burglars stole documentsfrom her apartment, police said today.;    The daily newspaper Haaretz saidsecret papers and tapes linked to the arms-for-hostages affair were stolen.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IRAN-CONTRA DOCUMENTS REPORTED STOLEN INISRAEL  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     It said the burglary occurred about six weeks ago -- roughly the same timeas a secret Israeli police probe launched into suspicions $2 million in armstransfer funds were stolen and diverted to bank accounts of Israelis involvedin the affair.;    National police spokeswoman Ruth Schlesinger would notconfirm or deny today that such an investigation is taking place.;    Haaretzquoted an unnamed police official as saying the burglary &quot;was the work ofprofessionals who knew exactly what they were looking for.&quot;;    Nir wascounter-terrorism adviser to prime ministers Shimon Peres and Yitzhak Shamir,and was involved in mediating some of Israel's sales of U.S. weapons to Iranafter January 1986.;    The main objective of the arms sales was to win therelease of Western hostages held by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon, but some ofthe funds were diverted to help the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.;    Nir waskilled in a plane crash in Mexico on Dec. 1, 1988. He had already leftgovernment service.;    His widow, Judith Nir-Moses, told police Tuesday thatpersonal papers were taken from her apartment in the Tel Aviv suburb of RamatGan, Tel Aviv police spokeswoman Dalia Gilad said.;    She said Nir-Mosesdidn't know when the burglary occurred.;    The spokeswoman said police found&quot;no signs of a break-in, no broken windows, broken locks or others signs ofviolence in the house.&quot; She would not give further details.;    Nir-Moses'telephone went unanswered today.;    Haaretz said the burglars took secretpapers and tapes concerning the Iran-Contra affair from a locked room in theapartment, leaving valuables untouched.;    It said the theft was discoveredonly recently because Nir-Moses rarely entered the locked room and didn'tspend much time in the apartment.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Jerusalem  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910718  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  3A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  346  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday July 18, 199100200229,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>